Based on the above visualizations, Since a lot of data is missing in Evaporation, Sunshine and Cloud, I have decided to drop those columns.

In [8]:
data.drop(columns=['Evaporation','Sunshine','Cloud'],inplace=True)

Dealing with missing values in Numerical variables

Now we have to deal with the missing values in the remaining columns. For numerical variables, I filled the missing values using the median of the column that is calculated after grouping the observations by Location variable.

In [9]:
for i in ['MinTemp', 'MaxTemp', 'Rainfall', 'WindSpeed', 'Humidity','Temp']:
    data[i]=data.groupby(['Location'])[i].transform(lambda x: x.fillna(x.median()))

After filling the missing values with median, there are still some missing values in Pressure and WindGustSpeed. This is because all the values associated with that particular Location are also missing. For those variables, I filled the missing values with median of the entire column.

In [10]:
for i in ['Pressure','WindGustSpeed']:
    data[i].fillna(data[i].median(),inplace=True)

Dealing with missing values in Categorical variables

We have four categorical variables in the data. Out of them three are independant variables and one is target variable.

There is no missing data in target variable, but for further use in modelling it is advisable to convert it to binary type. So target variable is replaced with 1 for No and 0 for Yes.

In [11]:
data.replace({'RainTomorrow':{'Yes':0,'No':1}},inplace=True)

For the rest of categorical variables, the missing values are replaced by the mode of the entire column.

In [12]:
for i in ['WindGustDir','WindDir','RainToday']:
    data[i].fillna(data[i].mode()[0],inplace=True)

Interpretation of the boxplots

For MinTemperature, we can observe that if it rains tomorrow if the MinTemperature is slightly be higher compared to no rain.

For MaxTemperature, we can observe that if it rains tomorrow if the MaxTemperature is lower compared to no rain.

For Pressure, we can observe that the range of Pressure is higher when there is no rain tomorrow.

For Rainfall, we can observe that when it rains tomorrow the range of Rainfall is higher.

For Temperature, we can observe that the Temperature is lower when there is rain tomorrow.

For Humidity, we can observe that the Humidity is very high when it rains compared to no rain.

For WindGustSpeed, we can observe that WindGustSpeed is higher when there is rain tomorrow.

For WindSpeed, we can observe that WindSpeed is slightly higher when it rains tomorrow

Finding outlier boundaries

In [15]:
for i in ['Rainfall','WindGustSpeed','WindSpeed','MaxTemp','MinTemp','Pressure','Humidity','Temp']:
    IQR = data[i].quantile(0.75) - data[i].quantile(0.25)
    Lower = data[i].quantile(0.25) - (IQR * 3)
    Upper = data[i].quantile(0.75) + (IQR * 3)
    print('{} outliers are values < {} or > {}'.format(i,Lower,Upper))

Rainfall outliers are values < -6.0 or > 8.0
WindGustSpeed outliers are values < -26.0 or > 107.0
WindSpeed outliers are values < -20.0 or > 57.0

Pressure outliers are values < 983.7999999999998 or > 1044.7000000000003
Humidity outliers are values < -47.0 or > 163.0

Removing outliers

In [16]:
def max_(x,var,upp):
    return np.where(x[var]>upp,upp,x[var])
In [17]:
data['Rainfall'] = max_(data,'Rainfall',8.8)
data['WindGustSpeed'] = max_(data,'WindGustSpeed',107)
data['WindSpeed'] = max_(data,'WindSpeed',57)
data['MinTemp'] = max_(data,'MinTemp',45.099999999999994)
data['MaxTemp'] = max_(data,'MaxTemp',58.400000000000006)
data['Pressure'] = max_(data,'Pressure',1048.9000000000003)
data['Humidity'] = max_(data,'Humidity',166.0)
data['Temp'] = max_(data,'Temp',55.30000000000001)

Performance Evaluation of the Decision Tree Model¶

Receiver Operating Characteristic (ROC) Curve

A ROC curve illustrates the ability of a binary classifier system as its discrimination threshold is varied.

The ROC curve is created by plotting the true positive rate (TPR) against the false positive rate (FPR) at various threshold values.

The true-positive rate is also known as sensitivity or recall. The false-positive rate is also known as (1 − specificity).

In [36]:
plt.figure(figsize=(12,7))
base_probs = [0 for _ in range(len(y_test))]

best_probs = dtree.predict_proba(X_test)
best_probs = best_probs[:, 1]

base_fpr, base_tpr, _ = roc_curve(y_test, base_probs)
best_fpr, best_tpr, _ = roc_curve(y_test, best_probs)

plt.plot(base_fpr, base_tpr, linestyle='dashdot', label='Base Decision Tree Model',color='Green')
plt.plot(best_fpr, best_tpr, marker='x', label='Best Decision Tree Model',color='Red',markeredgecolor='Blue',markersize=7)

plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate')
plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate')

plt.legend()

plt.show()

Area Under Curve

In [37]:

best_auc = roc_auc_score(y_test, best_probs)

print('Base Decision Tree Model: Auc = %.3f' % (base_auc))
print('Best Decision Tree Model: Auc = %.3f' % (best_auc))

Base Decision Tree Model: Auc = 0.500
Best Decision Tree Model: Auc = 0.835

An excellent model has AUC near to the 1 which means it has good measure of separability.

A poor model has AUC near to the 0 which means it has worst measure of separability.It is predicting 0s as 1s and 1s as 0s.

And when AUC is 0.5, it means model has no class separation capacity.

K-Means Clustering¶

The modelling that is presented in the report is my best model after hyperparameter tuning.

*I decided to remove categorical variables from the feature variables since we are supposed to use continuous variables for clustering.**

Also I got better results using unscaled data compared to scaled data. So I opted to use unscaled data.

Declaring feature and target variables

In [39]:
X = data.drop(['RainTomorrow','WindGustDir','WindDir','Location','RainToday'],axis=1)
y = data['RainTomorrow']

Elbow Method to find the optimal number of clusters

In [40]:
distortions = []

K = range(1,10)
for k in K:
    kmeans_model = KMeans(n_clusters=k)
    kmeans_model.fit(X)
    distortions.append(sum(np.min(cdist(X, kmeans_model.cluster_centers_, 'euclidean'), axis=1)) / X.shape[0])
plt.plot(K, distortions, 'bo-')
plt.xlabel("K - Number of Clusters")
plt.ylabel("Distortions")
Out[40]:
Text(0, 0.5, 'Distortions')

The optimal number of cluster is 2 since the curve abruptly decreases from the point denoting 2 clusters.

Splitting the data into train and test set

HAC¶

There are two types of HAC. One is Agglomerative Clustering and other is Decisive Clustering.

We use Agglomerative Clustering for our modelling.

For Hac I used the same feature and target variables as K-means but I added Raintoday to the feature variables after hyperparameter tuning.

Since HAC is computationally expensive $O(n^2)$ and can reach upto $O(n^2logn)$, I ran it on Google colab and pasted the required screenshots of the output.

Declaring feature and target variables

In [48]:
X = data.drop(['RainTomorrow','WindGustDir','WindDir','Location'],axis=1)
y = data['RainTomorrow']
In [49]:
X.replace({'RainToday':{'Yes':0,'No':1}},inplace=True)

Running the Agglomerative Clustering model

In [50]:
hclust = AgglomerativeClustering(n_clusters = 2, affinity='euclidean',linkage='ward').fit(X)

hclust.labels_

print('Precision score is {0:.2f} %\n'.format(precision_score((hclust.labels_),y)*100))
print('Recall score is {0:.2f} %\n'.format(recall_score((hclust.labels_),y)*100))

Repurpose unsupervised learning algorithms for classification¶

When we perform clustering on a binary classification problem, it divides the data into two clusters.

It means the data is classified into clusters based on the similarities between the feature variables.

From the clusters we can find out which one is 'Yes' or which one is 'No'.

There are a lot of measures that can judge the performance of algorithm like precision, recall, accuracy score, f1 score, entropy, gini and purity.
